http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Instrumental Music Curriculum Standards for grades 6-8.
Singing - Students will sing, alone and with others, a varied repertoire of music.
Demonstrate an understanding of pitch and rhythm through singing musical examples.
Demonstrate an understanding of harmony through singing musical examples of at least two parts in complexity.
Playing Instruments - Students will perform on instruments, alone and with others, a varied repertoire of music.
Demonstrate proper instrument care and maintenance.
Demonstrate continuing tonal development and an understanding of a characteristic tone quality.
Demonstrate fundamental technique on one's instrument.
Differentiate between correct and incorrect pitch and rhythm.
Demonstrate and understand musicality through style, dynamic control, tempo variation, and phrase shaping.
Apply techniques of sight-reading.
Perform scales (or rudiments) on one's instrument.
Improvising - Students will improvise melodies, variations, and accompaniments.
Improvise a simple rhythmic or melodic solo, through the medium of a traditional and/or jazz ensemble.
Experiment with variations on a given melody or rhythm.
Improvise a solo over a given chord progression, through the medium of a traditional and/or jazz ensemble.
Composing - Students will compose and arrange music within specified guidelines.
Compose music that demonstrates creativity.
Create an arrangement for an appropriate performance medium.
Reading and Notation - Students will read and notate music.
Identify and interpret standard musical notation.
Listening to, analyzing, and describing music - Students will listen to, analyze, and describe music.
Describe musical examples using appropriate vocabulary/terminology.
Analyze specific events in a given musical example.
Evaluating - Students will evaluate music and music performances.
Describe the quality of a musical performance using selected criteria.
Evaluate the quality and effectiveness of one's own and another's performance using selected criteria.
Interdisciplinary Connections - Students will understand relationships between music, the other arts, and disciplines outside the arts.
Identify and explain how elements of music (e.g., color, balance, rhythm, texture) are used in similar and distinctive ways in other arts disciplines.
Compare ways in which the subject matter of other disciplines is interrelated with those of music.
Discuss the role of technology in creating, producing, and listening to music.
Historical and Cultural Relationships - Students will understand music in relation to history and culture.
Recognize and describe distinguishing characteristics of music from various historical periods.
Describe music from various cultures.
Discuss the role of music in society throughout history.
